answers.body_markdown:
According to the example in [Secure REST API using Spring Security 5 and Azure Active Directory][1], it mentioned using @PreAuthorize Annotation in the Controller code.

    import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
    import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.ResponseBody;
    import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;
    import org.springframework.security.access.prepost.PreAuthorize;
    
    @RestController
    public class HelloController {
         @GetMapping(&quot;Admin&quot;)
         @ResponseBody
         @PreAuthorize(&quot;hasAuthority(&#39;APPROLE_Admin&#39;)&quot;)
         public String Admin() {
             return &quot;Admin message&quot;;
         }
    }

For more details about this annotation, please kindly check
- [org.springframework.security.access.prepost.PreAuthorize][2]
- [Spring Method Security with PreAuthorize][3]


  [1]: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/developer/java/spring-framework/configure-spring-boot-starter-java-app-with-azure-active-directory#configure-and-compile-your-app
  [2]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-security/site/docs/4.2.3.RELEASE/apidocs/org/springframework/security/access/prepost/PreAuthorize.html
  [3]: https://developer.okta.com/blog/2019/06/20/spring-preauthorize

